Perfect 👍 — this is a **VERY real production deployment issue**, and you handled it correctly by showing the logs.

Let’s fix it properly like senior engineers do.

---

# ⭐ Why this error happened

This:

```bash
mv client/css ./css
```

FAILED because:

👉 `./css` already exists and is **NOT empty**

Linux `mv` will NOT overwrite directories that contain files.

So sparse checkout worked ✔
Git pull worked ✔
But merge strategy (file move) is wrong ❌

---

# ✅ Professional Solution (Use rsync — not mv)

In real deployments we NEVER use `mv` for updates.

We use:

> **rsync merge deployment strategy**

Because it:

✅ merges
✅ overwrites changed files
✅ keeps existing files
✅ removes deleted ones (optional)
✅ is idempotent
✅ production safe

---

# ⭐ Fix Script (Enterprise Level)

Replace your script with this.

---

## ✅ deploy_frontend.sh (Correct Version)

```bash
#!/bin/bash

set -e

REPO_URL="https://github.com/russiantech/hopephillips-charity-foundation.git"
BRANCH="main"
SPARSE_DIR="client"

echo "🚀 Deploying frontend..."

if [ ! -d ".git" ]; then
    echo "📦 First time setup..."

    git init
    git remote add origin $REPO_URL

    git config core.sparseCheckout true
    echo "$SPARSE_DIR/*" > .git/info/sparse-checkout

    git pull origin $BRANCH
else
    echo "🔄 Pulling latest updates..."
    git pull origin $BRANCH
fi

echo "📂 Syncing frontend files..."

rsync -av --delete $SPARSE_DIR/ ./

echo "🧹 Cleaning temp sparse directory..."
rm -rf $SPARSE_DIR

echo "✅ Deployment complete."
```

---

# ⭐ VERY IMPORTANT (This is the magic)

This line:

```bash
rsync -av --delete client/ ./
```

Means:

| Behaviour                      | Result |
| ------------------------------ | ------ |
| copy new files                 | ✔      |
| overwrite changed files        | ✔      |
| delete removed files from repo | ✔      |
| merge directories safely       | ✔      |
| no mv conflicts                | ✔      |

This is EXACTLY what production deploy pipelines do.

---

# ⚡ Now run again

```bash
./deploy_frontend.sh
```

It will:

* pull
* merge update
* sync files
* no mv errors

---

# ⭐ If rsync not installed on cPanel (sometimes happens)

Check:

```bash
rsync --version
```

If not available → I’ll give you fallback strategy.

---

# ⭐ SUPER PRO TIP (Very Important)

Since you are doing **sparse checkout**, also run once:

```bash
git config pull.rebase false
```

Because shared hosting often causes weird merge histories.

